We have seen in the previous notebook that, among the variables that exist in both the approved loans and declined loans data, the credit risk score is incomparable across these two groups because one uses letter grades while the other uses numerical values (FICO score). Before we fit logistic regression or some kind of classification algorithms onto the data, I want to check if the variation in credit risk variable is explained well by the other variables. That is, I want to check if credit risk is multicollinear with other variables of interest.

After fitting Simple Linear Regression on each of Risk Score v.s. other variable of interest (requested loan amount, dti, employment length), I discovered that individual variables don't really explain well the variation in risk score. Each of the variable is not that mutlicollinear with risk score. Then, the question is does the combination of those three variables explain well the variation in risk score?

In [49]:
# Keeping only rows that have data on both risk score, amount requested, dti, employment Length so that 
# we can use it for simple linear regression
declined_df2_all_three = declined_df2.copy()[declined_df2.copy().Risk_Score.notnull()]
declined_df2_all_three = declined_df2_all_three.copy()[declined_df2_all_three.copy()['Employment Length Encoded'].notnull()]
declined_df2_all_three = declined_df2_all_three.copy()[declined_df2_all_three.copy()['Amount Requested'].notnull()]
declined_df2_all_three = declined_df2_all_three.copy()[declined_df2_all_three.copy()['dti'].notnull()]
In [50]:
lr_all_three = LinearRegression()
In [56]:
lr_all_three.fit(declined_df2_all_three[['Amount Requested','dti','Employment Length Encoded']].values.reshape(len(declined_df2_all_three),3),
                      declined_df2_all_three['Risk_Score'].values.reshape(-1,1))
Out[56]:
LinearRegression(copy_X=True, fit_intercept=True, n_jobs=1, normalize=False)
In [57]:
# Coefficient of dti
lr_all_three.coef_
Out[57]:
array([[  1.96059442e-03,  -9.25781787e-06,   5.73066386e+00]])
In [58]:
# coefficient of determination R-Squared
lr_all_three.score(declined_df2_all_three[['Amount Requested','dti','Employment Length Encoded']].values.reshape(len(declined_df2_all_three),3),
                      declined_df2_all_three['Risk_Score'].values.reshape(-1,1))
Out[58]:
0.07248597426174197

Even when three of the variables are considered for together in the model, the MLR model only explains 7.2% of the variation in Risk Score
